<section xml:id="trigonometric_identities">
  <title>Trigonometric Identities</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we explore trigonometric identities and formulas, which are essential tools for algebraically manipulating and solving complex trigonometric equations. These identities and formulas provide deeper insights and allow us to more accurately model the world around us.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-fundamental-trig-identities">
    <title>Fundamental Trigonometric Identities</title>
    <p>
      An <term>identity</term> in mathematics is an equation that remains true for every valid values of its variables. We begin by reviewing identities from <xref ref="trigonometric_functions"/> , collectively known as the fundamental trigonometric identities.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-fundamental-trig-identities">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>fundamental trigonometric identities</h>
          </idx>
          The <term>fundamental trigonometric identities</term> are
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Reciprocal Identities</term> (<xref ref="def_reciprocal-identities"/>)
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\csc\theta} \amp  \cos\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\sec\theta} \amp  \tan\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\cot\theta}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\sin\theta} \amp  \sec\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\cos\theta} \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\tan\theta}</mrow>
                </md> 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Quotient Identities</term> (<xref ref="def_quotient-identities"/>)
                <md>
                  <mrow>\tan\theta \amp =\dfrac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta} \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\dfrac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Pythagorean Identities</term> (<xref ref="def_pythagorean-identity"/>)
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sin^2\theta+\cos^2\theta \amp = 1 </mrow>
                  <mrow> 1+\tan^2\theta \amp = \sec^2\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow> 1+\cot^2\theta \amp = \csc^2\theta</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Odd-Even Properties</term> (<xref ref="def-even-odd-trig"/>)
              </p>
              <p>
                The cosine and secant functions are <term>even</term>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\cos(-\theta)\amp =\cos\theta \amp  \sec(-\theta)\amp =\sec\theta</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
              <p>
                The sine, cosecant, tangent, and cotangent functions are <term>odd</term>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sin(-\theta)\amp =-\sin\theta \amp  \csc(-\theta)\amp =-\csc(\theta)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\tan(-\theta)\amp =-\tan\theta \amp  \cot(-\theta)\amp =-\cot(\theta)</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Cofunction Identities</term> (<xref ref="def_cofunction-identities"/>)
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp \cos\theta\amp =\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\tan\theta\amp =\cot\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp \cot\theta\amp =\tan\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sec\theta\amp =\csc\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp \csc\theta\amp =\sec\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>






